A-3. That (A) implies (B) follows from the fact that subsequences of a convergent sequence converge to the limit of the sequence. We simplify the notation by setting \( c_{r}=\exp i a_{r} \) and \( S(t)=c_{1}+c_{2}+\cdots+c_{t} \). Note that \( \left|c_{r}\right|=1 \) and \( |S(t+k)-S(t)| \leqq k \). Suppose now that (B) holds and write \( m=n^{2}+k \), where \( 0 \leqq k \leqq 2 n \).
\[
\begin{aligned}
\left|\frac{S(m)}{m}-\frac{S\left(n^{2}\right)}{n^{2}}\right| & \leqq\left|\frac{S(m)}{m}-\frac{S\left(n^{2}\right)}{m}\right|+\left|\frac{S\left(n^{2}\right)}{n^{2}}-\frac{S\left(n^{2}\right)}{m}\right| \\
& \leqq \frac{k}{m}+n^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n^{2}}-\frac{1}{m}\right)=\frac{k+m-n^{2}}{m}=\frac{2 k}{m} \leqq \frac{4 n}{n^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

We conclude that \( \lim _{m \rightarrow \infty}\left(S(m) / m-S\left(n^{2}\right) / n^{2}\right)=0 \) or that \( S(m) / m \) converges to \( \alpha \).

